RBAC with Kubernetes — Role, ClusterRole, RoleBinding, and ClusterRoleBinding.

What is RBAC in general? 

RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) is a security model used to control who can access what resources based on their role within an organization.
Instead of assigning permissions directly to each user, permissions are assigned to roles, and users are assigned to those roles.

Basic Components
User: A person, application, or service account.
Example: Alice, Bob, Jenkins service account.

Role: A collection of permissions.
Example:
Administrator
Developer
Read-Only User

Permission: An action that can be performed on a resource.
Examples:
Read files
Create virtual machines
Delete users

Resource:
The object being accessed.
Examples:
Server
Database
Kubernetes Pod
Application

Example:
Suppose a company has three roles:

Role	Permissions:
1. Admin	Full access
2. Developer	Create and modify applications
3. Viewer	Read-only access

Users are assigned roles:

User	   Role
Alice	   Admin
Bob	     Developer
Charlie	 Viewer

When Bob logs in, he automatically gets all permissions assigned to the Developer role.

Why RBAC is Used: 
Simplifies permission management.
Enforces the principle of least privilege.
Reduces administrative effort.
Improves security and compliance.
Makes auditing easier.
